into something else.

00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:35.910
That's what people don't know.

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:37.800
They say, oh, we
don't like leftovers,

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:40.800
but good cooks know that you
can take leftovers and turn it

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.030
into something else.

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:43.890
What is salad nicoise?

00:15:43.890 --> 00:15:47.600
Leftover green beans,
leftover potatoes.

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:49.820
Throw a can of tuna fish on.

00:15:49.820 --> 00:15:50.430
Am I right?

00:15:55.980 --> 00:16:02.670
The sources of food waste are
the farm, the distribution

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:05.520
center, the grocery
store, and the home.

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:10.800
And so if we can try and
pick up at those places

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:14.250
and teach people how to
reuse their leftovers

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:16.950
and not buy too much
that they don't need

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:19.860
and don't worry about
expiration dates,

00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:22.380
then we can help to
avoid food waste.

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:24.540
What can we do
about people here?

00:16:24.540 --> 00:16:30.090
So I am 70-fucking-6
years old, and I'm

00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:32.820
at the age where if
I go to a restaurant,

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:34.590
I don't eat all the food.

00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:39.750
So what's happening for my
generation is a lot of people

00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:43.650
will eat half their
portion of chicken or fish

00:16:43.650 --> 00:16:46.830
or whatever it is and
then ask for a little box

00:16:46.830 --> 00:16:49.530
to take the rest
home in, then they

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:51.480
eat it cold for
lunch the next day.

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:54.000
That's what older women do.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:59.610
But how can you
teach Googlers not

00:16:59.610 --> 00:17:04.510
to take so much on their
plate and then they think,

00:17:04.510 --> 00:17:07.380
oh, well it's being composted.

00:17:07.380 --> 00:17:09.720
Still, you don't need
to take so much food

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:13.200
if you're not going to eat it.

00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:15.150
How do you teach
people not to do it?

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:16.319
I don't know.

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:19.650
You tell them about
the 76-year-old lady

00:17:19.650 --> 00:17:23.369
that has a little box to
take home and eat it cold

00:17:23.369 --> 00:17:24.089
the next day.

00:17:27.329 --> 00:17:39.380
OK, next-- what we all know
is that if I take a plate of--

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:45.560
today, I had delicious lentils
and noodles here for lunch.

00:17:45.560 --> 00:17:48.740
If I take too much
food on my plate,

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:51.020
I can put it in a little
box and take it home.

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:54.200
But the food that was all
out on the buffet that

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:58.940
is not reusable for
another day, all

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:00.725
can be packaged and donated.

00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:11.690
And that's why we have
so much tins of food

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:15.650
from businesses like yours
that we pick up and take

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:18.530
to the shelters.

00:18:18.530 --> 00:18:23.450
This is a list of
the five places

00:18:23.450 --> 00:18:28.080
that your food is donated
to five days a week.

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:30.590
So you don't have
to hang out there.

00:18:30.590 --> 00:18:32.861
Come on, stand up.

00:18:32.861 --> 00:18:33.980
Come on, stand up.

00:18:33.980 --> 00:18:35.900
Look, we're the
Christmas girls--

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:38.930
green and red.

00:18:38.930 --> 00:18:45.020
So the last place,
the Derek Silva,

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:48.440
it's 68 units of
affordable housing.

00:18:48.440 --> 00:18:53.270
It is for people
living with HIV/AIDS.

00:18:53.270 --> 00:19:00.520
And so the food that Google is
donating through Food Runners,

00:19:00.520 --> 00:19:04.460
every day has been taken
to those five places--

00:19:04.460 --> 00:19:08.810
an agency serving
hot meals to anybody

00:19:08.810 --> 00:19:11.960
that comes to the door,
a mental health treatment

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:18.500
program for ex-cons, a church
serving meals to the homeless,

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:23.570
Canon Kip is elderly,
and Derek Silva is HIV.

00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:28.990
So those people are totally
spoiled by your food.

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:31.970
And could we take
more from Google?

00:19:31.970 --> 00:19:33.620
The answer is yes.

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:35.610
We can take the yogurt
that's over there.

00:19:35.610 --> 00:19:40.040
We can take the fruit
that's in the cafes.

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:43.070
We can take everything
that has not

00:19:43.070 --> 00:19:45.220
been served on a
plate to somebody

00:19:45.220 --> 00:19:46.970
sitting there, spitting
on it, and putting

00:19:46.970 --> 00:19:48.920
their fingers in it, OK?

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:54.830
For instance, I'll take
those pumpkins when I leave.

00:19:54.830 --> 00:19:55.881
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:56.380 --> 00:19:58.760
I'll put those in my purse.

00:19:58.760 --> 00:20:02.270
All buffet food is donatable.

00:20:02.270 --> 00:20:05.510
We pick up at the Hilton today.

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:08.540
We're picking up at
the Ritz-Carlton today.

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:18.170
From the Ritz-Carlton, it's
taken about nine months, where,

00:20:18.170 --> 00:20:21.590
first, we got their
leftover banquet food,

00:20:21.590 --> 00:20:23.450
and now we're getting
the leftover food

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:25.940
from the takeout places.

00:20:25.940 --> 00:20:29.390
But it's just amazing
the misinformation

00:20:29.390 --> 00:20:30.800
that people have.

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:33.020
I heard once about somebody--

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:36.700
it was actually a
Bon Appétit company.

00:20:36.700 --> 00:20:41.135
Down in the peninsula, Bon
Appétit is the food provider.

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:48.890
They put out yogurt in an ice
bath, and when the ice melts,

00:20:48.890 --> 00:20:50.510
they throw the yogurt out.

00:20:50.510 --> 00:20:52.460
I mean, that's ridiculous.

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:54.395
Yogurt is bacteria.

00:20:54.395 --> 00:20:55.270
Yogurt keeps forever.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:56.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:57.170 --> 00:21:00.830
So no food needs
to be thrown away.

00:21:00.830 --> 00:21:02.860
You can donate it.

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:06.830
Just put it in a package
and call Food Runners.

00:21:06.830 --> 00:21:09.350
So can I have the next--

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:11.760
the next one's probably a photo.

00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:13.310
So what is food waste?

00:21:13.310 --> 00:21:17.420
Food waste has
many sources, but I

00:21:17.420 --> 00:21:22.070
think it's kind of uneducated
people that don't know

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:24.470
or it's people that don't care--

00:21:24.470 --> 00:21:30.290
one more-- or they're in the
habit of throwing food away.

00:21:36.732 --> 00:21:41.870
It takes a long time to get
people to change their habits.

00:21:41.870 --> 00:21:50.390
And so the habits are take only
what you think you can eat,

00:21:50.390 --> 00:21:58.790
save the rest to
donate, and see that

00:21:58.790 --> 00:22:01.820
a responsible organization,
like Food Runners,

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:05.480
picks it up and takes it
where it can best be used.

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:13.010
The next thing that I think what
you can help Food Runners with

00:22:13.010 --> 00:22:16.970
is, first of all, maybe we could
pass these out to everybody

00:22:16.970 --> 00:22:19.170
and pass these out to everybody.

00:22:19.170 --> 00:22:26.180
So the deal is that because
I'm an old secretary,

00:22:26.180 --> 00:22:33.540
I do things with
cards and brochures,

00:22:33.540 --> 00:22:35.400
but hold on to these.

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:38.170
And so we're still kind
of in the process--

00:22:38.170 --> 00:22:41.080
at Food Runners, we're
kind of in the "pro-cess"--

00:22:41.080 --> 00:22:44.160
that's Canadian for process.

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:48.420
We're kind of in the process
of trying to get more

00:22:48.420 --> 00:22:50.220
into the new technology.

00:22:50.220 --> 00:22:57.430
For instance, we are
working on an app,

00:22:57.430 --> 00:23:01.620
but currently, people can donate
through the website or the app.

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:04.410
We still have a phone
with an answering service.

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:07.740
So people can call
and leave a message

00:23:07.740 --> 00:23:09.360
on an answering service--

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:12.700
I mean a voicemail.

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:18.310
But I think how you
can help, as Googlers,

00:23:18.310 --> 00:23:22.650
as San Franciscans, and
as concerned people,

00:23:22.650 --> 00:23:26.310
is first of all,
tell your friends.

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:28.350
Tell your friends.

00:23:28.350 --> 00:23:36.090
The best volunteers for us are
people who are in between jobs.

00:23:36.090 --> 00:23:37.950
People who are in between jobs.

00:23:37.950 --> 00:23:38.730
That's fine.

00:23:38.730 --> 00:23:40.980
People who are in
between jobs or recently

00:23:40.980 --> 00:23:43.200
retired make really
good volunteers

00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:45.820
because they're used to
getting up and going somewhere.

00:23:45.820 --> 00:23:48.300
So if you know anybody
that's recently

00:23:48.300 --> 00:23:54.110
retired or between jobs, and
they have their own vehicle,

00:23:54.110 --> 00:23:56.490
this is a really good
place to volunteer,

00:23:56.490 --> 00:23:58.590
is with Food Runners.

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:03.960
We also could use help
through social media

00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:08.880
by taking pictures of the food
you're donating and saying,

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:12.000
this is going to neighborhood
shelters through Food Runners.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:15.990
So we could use the
help with social media.

00:24:15.990 --> 00:24:22.170
We can use help with telling
everybody you know with food.

00:24:22.170 --> 00:24:25.815
And what else can
we use help with?

00:24:25.815 --> 00:24:28.586
If you know anybody with a car--

00:24:28.586 --> 00:24:30.210
So I want to tell
you a little bit more

00:24:30.210 --> 00:24:33.900
about some of the people
that are volunteers for us.

00:24:33.900 --> 00:24:39.060
There's a man who came here--
actually, I shouldn't say this,

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:41.520
but he also came
here in the '50s

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:43.830
and earned his living
as a drug dealer.

00:24:43.830 --> 00:24:48.060
And then he went into the
waterproofing and painting

00:24:48.060 --> 00:24:49.110
business.

00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:55.290
And this guy has been picking
up, at the Ferry Plaza Farmers

00:24:55.290 --> 00:25:00.030
Market, all the leftover
food from the farmers

00:25:00.030 --> 00:25:05.610
every Saturday whenever
he's in San Francisco.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:07.320
He goes and gets the truck.

00:25:07.320 --> 00:25:10.140
We use a truck for
large donations.

00:25:10.140 --> 00:25:12.990
He goes and gets the
truck, and he's a Brit.

00:25:12.990 --> 00:25:15.330
So you can see him
at 1:30, 12:30,

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:17.870
1:00 o'clock at the
Ferry building going,

00:25:17.870 --> 00:25:23.520
Food Runners, Food Runners,
bring out your food.

00:25:23.520 --> 00:25:26.970
So it takes him
four hours every day

00:25:26.970 --> 00:25:30.870
to deliver all the food that
the farmers bring him because he

00:25:30.870 --> 00:25:34.290
has a relationship with them.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:36.255
And then the farmers
at the Ferry building

00:25:36.255 --> 00:25:40.430
bring him up even extra
food on Saturdays.

00:25:40.430 --> 00:25:42.360
There is another
guy, kind of who

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:44.430
I would call a trust fund baby.

00:25:44.430 --> 00:25:48.150
He's a well-to-do
man who lives out

00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:50.880
on Washington Street
in Pacific Heights

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:53.940
and he has a
17-year-old daughter.

00:25:53.940 --> 00:25:57.300
And he and his daughter go
on food runs every Saturday.

00:26:02.070 --> 00:26:06.570
He does Saturday at Kara's
Cupcakes on Steiner Street--

00:26:06.570 --> 00:26:07.770
no, Scott Street.

00:26:07.770 --> 00:26:11.080
And he takes bread
and pastries out

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:16.760
to the veteran's
home up on Presidio.

00:26:16.760 --> 00:26:17.760
That's on Saturday.

00:26:17.760 --> 00:26:21.060
On Sunday, he goes to the
farmers market at Fort Mason

00:26:21.060 --> 00:26:23.280
and picks up all
their leftover foods

00:26:23.280 --> 00:26:26.380
and takes it to a place
called Walden House--

00:26:26.380 --> 00:26:28.130
that I call Walden house--

00:26:28.130 --> 00:26:29.335
on Hays and Fillmore.

00:26:33.480 --> 00:26:36.120
And then there's a guy
called Sam Haskins.

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:41.070
Sam Haskins will go
today at about 3:30

00:26:41.070 --> 00:26:43.080
to a restaurant
called [INAUDIBLE],,

00:26:43.080 --> 00:26:45.890
who makes foil trays
of food for him.

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:52.590
He's a lawyer who writes books.

00:26:52.590 --> 00:26:54.900
We also have women
doing deliveries, too.

00:26:58.740 --> 00:27:01.380
The volunteers for Food
Runners, some of them

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:04.740
have been volunteers
for 30 years.

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:06.540
Some people like to
know that they're

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:09.750
going to go every
Friday at 4:00 o'clock

00:27:09.750 --> 00:27:11.460
in the afternoon to
pick up the leftover

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:15.090
food at the Williams-Sonoma
corporate office.

00:27:15.090 --> 00:27:18.930
And some people like to know
that they're going to go.

00:27:18.930 --> 00:27:20.880
Oh, there's a brand new place.

00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:22.650
I don't know if
you've been to it.

00:27:22.650 --> 00:27:26.970
It's called Meraki.

00:27:26.970 --> 00:27:32.800
It's a society deli on Post
between Larkin And Hyde

00:27:32.800 --> 00:27:35.470
that just opened two weeks ago.

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:38.500
A guy called Stanlee
Gatti is the owner,

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:41.590
and he brought in a bunch
of New York hotshots

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:47.110
and they put all this kombucha,
and sauerkraut, and chia seeds,

00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:48.940
and all these trendy
food in there.

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:55.120
Then you go, what are
they doing on Post

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:56.230
between Larkin and Hyde?

00:27:56.230 --> 00:28:00.190
It's kind of like a
renters neighborhood,

00:28:00.190 --> 00:28:03.740
but they've got all the society
people coming in their limos,

00:28:03.740 --> 00:28:06.580
and they send their
chauffeurs to pick up food.

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:12.910
But that new deli on Post
Street is giving off all

00:28:12.910 --> 00:28:15.220
their leftover food--

00:28:15.220 --> 00:28:16.540
I went and picked up myself--

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:20.402
every night at 9:00 o'clock
the first week they were open.

00:28:20.402 --> 00:28:22.110
And now, they save
the food in the cooler

00:28:22.110 --> 00:28:24.520
and we pick it up the next day.

00:28:24.520 --> 00:28:25.650
Have you been there?

00:28:25.650 --> 00:28:27.993
AUDIENCE: No, I was just
thinking it might the old Fleur

00:28:27.993 --> 00:28:29.840
de Lis spot.

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:31.090
MARY RISLEY: That's on Sutter.

00:28:31.090 --> 00:28:32.170
This is Post.

00:28:32.170 --> 00:28:35.920
It's a kind of crappy building.

00:28:35.920 --> 00:28:40.068
So I got to tell more jokes
or he got a phone call.

00:28:40.068 --> 00:28:41.472
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:42.760 --> 00:28:49.690
So anyway, we pick up at
bakeries, grocery stores,

00:28:49.690 --> 00:28:52.390
delis like this
place, Mollie Stone's.

00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:53.500
So listen to this.

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:58.770
So I am in Mollie Stone's
all the time on California

00:28:58.770 --> 00:29:02.350
and Franklin, and
it's taken me 10 years

00:29:02.350 --> 00:29:07.940
to get the Mollie Stone's to
donate their leftover food.

00:29:07.940 --> 00:29:11.530
And what changed their mind was
I named my dog Mollie Stone.

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:14.075
I got a new dog last year
and called it Mollie Stone.

00:29:14.075 --> 00:29:16.311
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:16.810 --> 00:29:19.930
But you know, it's hard
to convince people,

00:29:19.930 --> 00:29:22.010
as I said, to
change their habits,

00:29:22.010 --> 00:29:27.180
but we have 200 volunteers.

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:32.710
We're picking up
500 times a week

00:29:32.710 --> 00:29:36.580
with a van, a truck,
and our volunteers

00:29:36.580 --> 00:29:40.570
with regular runs, and then
other people that are on-call.

00:29:40.570 --> 00:29:43.090
Some people just like to be
on-call, get in their car

00:29:43.090 --> 00:29:44.270
and go.

00:29:44.270 --> 00:29:46.750
And we also pick up--

00:29:46.750 --> 00:29:50.710
I talked about the
Ritz-Carlton and the Hilton.

00:29:50.710 --> 00:29:52.900
We also pick up from caterers.

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:56.080
There's a big caterer
called Dan McCall,

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:59.620
who has a commissary
kitchen on 17th Street.

00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:03.880
He will take back his leftover
food to the commissary kitchen,

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:06.890
and we'll come the next
day and pick it up.

00:30:06.890 --> 00:30:11.350
There's another caterer called
Paula LeDuc out of Emeryville.

00:30:11.350 --> 00:30:13.630
So she doesn't take
it back to Emeryville.

00:30:13.630 --> 00:30:17.770
She calls us and we pick
it up at 1:30 at night.

00:30:17.770 --> 00:30:20.140
So somebody suggested
recently that maybe we

00:30:20.140 --> 00:30:21.910
should have Uber drivers.

00:30:21.910 --> 00:30:23.110
We should have Uber--

00:30:23.110 --> 00:30:26.230
because of their
bad reputation--

00:30:26.230 --> 00:30:32.530
sponsor cars going around
and picking up food for us.

00:30:32.530 --> 00:30:35.740
And you go, oh, I
don't know because they

00:30:35.740 --> 00:30:40.610
might Get creamed chicken all
over the back of their car.

00:30:40.610 --> 00:30:47.590
So anyway, the regular
people, we have 500 people--

00:30:47.590 --> 00:30:50.830
no, 150 people, a
truck driver, a van,

00:30:50.830 --> 00:30:53.410
and a couple of cargo
bikes going around

00:30:53.410 --> 00:30:57.940
and picking up food either as
regular runners or volunteers.

