00:33:42.430 --> 00:33:47.180
I don't think that has anything
to do with rescuing food.

00:33:47.180 --> 00:33:48.160
Listen to this.

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:53.800
In San Francisco,
it's well-known

00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:57.400
that the homeless people
are the pickiest eaters.

00:33:57.400 --> 00:34:00.620
So if you were to go serve
food at Glide or St. Anthony

00:34:00.620 --> 00:34:03.010
or Martin de Porres
you do have people

00:34:03.010 --> 00:34:06.460
going through the line saying,
does that have sugar in it?

00:34:06.460 --> 00:34:08.290
Does that have gluten in it?

00:34:12.760 --> 00:34:17.500
Even the homeless and the
hungry are picky eaters here.

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:22.690
But I think vegetarianism
is a personal choice.

00:34:22.690 --> 00:34:23.768
Yes sweetheart?

00:34:27.480 --> 00:34:30.699
AUDIENCE: Hello, hello,
hello, testing, testing.

00:34:30.699 --> 00:34:34.870
I was just curious, what
inspired the inspiration

00:34:34.870 --> 00:34:36.507
for the initial--

00:34:36.507 --> 00:34:37.090
here you were.

00:34:37.090 --> 00:34:40.374
You were running
a cooking school.

00:34:40.374 --> 00:34:42.290
And then you decided to
start this Food Runner

00:34:42.290 --> 00:34:42.956
some time later.

00:34:42.956 --> 00:34:44.320
You said 1987.

00:34:44.320 --> 00:34:45.880
What was happening
at that moment?

00:34:45.880 --> 00:34:48.100
What did you see?

00:34:48.100 --> 00:34:52.150
MARY RISLEY: Quite frankly I
used to stop in my red Alfa

00:34:52.150 --> 00:34:54.969
Romeo at the corner of--

00:34:54.969 --> 00:34:58.300
every day I crossed the corner
of Chestnut and Columbus.

00:34:58.300 --> 00:35:00.550
And you'd see people going
through the garbage looking

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:01.720
for food.

00:35:01.720 --> 00:35:06.970
And so what I did, at one
time at my cooking school

00:35:06.970 --> 00:35:10.300
we did a two-day
wedding-cake workshop.

00:35:10.300 --> 00:35:14.890
And so at the end of the
two days, we cut into them,

00:35:14.890 --> 00:35:18.250
we tasted it, but I had
seven wedding cakes.

00:35:18.250 --> 00:35:20.560
Do I drive them to Glide?

00:35:20.560 --> 00:35:24.280
Do I give them to the staff?

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:28.880
Or do I throw them
in the garbage?

00:35:28.880 --> 00:35:32.530
And so I thought, there
must be other people

00:35:32.530 --> 00:35:35.420
in the food business that
have that same question.

00:35:35.420 --> 00:35:38.320
And the truth is I
still have that car too.

00:35:38.320 --> 00:35:42.400
And I still have buttercream
all over the steering wheel

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:43.910
because I drove it to Glide.

00:35:43.910 --> 00:35:47.620
I drove those wedding
cakes to Glide in 1986.

00:35:47.620 --> 00:35:50.560
I approached the
mayor's office--

00:35:50.560 --> 00:35:52.780
Dianne Feinstein
was the mayor then--

00:35:52.780 --> 00:35:56.470
and said I have food
connections, can we help?

00:35:56.470 --> 00:35:59.350
And she introduced me
to a woman in Berkeley

00:35:59.350 --> 00:36:04.060
who was kind of a whole
Mother Earth type of woman.

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:06.260
And she taught me
how to do this.

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:10.142
And so we started with a small
group of people, Food Runners,

00:36:10.142 --> 00:36:12.100
saying we're going to
provide this free service

00:36:12.100 --> 00:36:14.380
to any business
in San Francisco.

00:36:14.380 --> 00:36:20.450
And so what do you do if you
have a party in your home

00:36:20.450 --> 00:36:23.650
and then not everybody comes?

00:36:23.650 --> 00:36:28.950
So what you can do as
a home cook is package

00:36:28.950 --> 00:36:34.930
the food and you can look on
foodrunners.org, the website,

00:36:34.930 --> 00:36:37.300
and it'll tell you where
your neighborhood place

00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:38.599
that you can take food to.

00:36:38.599 --> 00:36:40.390
If you live in North
Beach, you can take it

00:36:40.390 --> 00:36:41.710
to North Beach Citizens.

00:36:41.710 --> 00:36:45.340
If you live out by-- there's
a place called Edgewood out

00:36:45.340 --> 00:36:47.110
by the zoo, things like that.

00:36:47.110 --> 00:36:51.820
So we can't pick up in homes,
but home food can be taken.

00:36:55.060 --> 00:36:57.077
OK, does that answer
your question?

00:36:57.077 --> 00:36:57.660
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:36:57.660 --> 00:36:59.410
And one more quick
question-- have

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:01.527
you seen the
documentary "Wasted",

00:37:01.527 --> 00:37:03.610
and what do you think of
Anthony fucking Bourdain?

00:37:03.610 --> 00:37:05.845
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:07.087 --> 00:37:08.920
MARY RISLEY: I haven't
seen the documentary.

00:37:08.920 --> 00:37:10.930
They asked me if I would in it.

00:37:10.930 --> 00:37:14.645
And he's definitely a newcomer
to the whole thing, you know?

00:37:14.645 --> 00:37:15.895
Have you seen the documentary?

00:37:15.895 --> 00:37:16.660
AUDIENCE: We just saw it.

00:37:16.660 --> 00:37:17.700
MARY RISLEY: Was it any good?

00:37:17.700 --> 00:37:18.730
AUDIENCE: It was
actually pretty good.

00:37:18.730 --> 00:37:19.670
MARY RISLEY: Yeah.

00:37:19.670 --> 00:37:22.810
So Tony Bourdain, as you
know, has made his reputation

00:37:22.810 --> 00:37:26.320
as a bad boy, throwing
cigarette butts in melted butter

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:30.280
and restaurants where he worked
in Grand Central Station.

00:37:30.280 --> 00:37:34.960
But he has great writers
and great producers.

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:38.000
And so if they're helping the
food movement, God bless them.

00:37:45.132 --> 00:37:46.090
AUDIENCE: Hello, hello.

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:46.940
MARY RISLEY: Hi.

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:47.620
Hello, hello.

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:48.812
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:37:48.812 --> 00:37:50.770
I was introduced to your
company about 10 years

00:37:50.770 --> 00:37:52.630
while working in grocery,
working on Whole Foods.

00:37:52.630 --> 00:37:54.254
And so it was a very
interesting moment

00:37:54.254 --> 00:37:56.547
of just like the
idea of food waste

00:37:56.547 --> 00:37:57.880
and how it's being acknowledged.

00:37:57.880 --> 00:37:59.440
And it seems perhaps
like you guys

00:37:59.440 --> 00:38:01.570
could have been kind of
like setting an industry

00:38:01.570 --> 00:38:02.357
standard for such.

00:38:02.357 --> 00:38:03.190
And I'm curious if--

00:38:03.190 --> 00:38:04.052
MARY RISLEY: I think we were--

00:38:04.052 --> 00:38:04.350
AUDIENCE: --other cities--

00:38:04.350 --> 00:38:05.620
MARY RISLEY: --one of the
first in the country, yeah.

00:38:05.620 --> 00:38:07.630
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so have
other cities come to you?

00:38:07.630 --> 00:38:09.088
MARY RISLEY: I
think totally, yeah.

00:38:09.088 --> 00:38:15.850
So what happens is there is
now a kind of a food waste--

00:38:15.850 --> 00:38:20.350
I mean a food recovery group in
Sonoma County that I trained.

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:22.560
There's one in Marin
County that I helped train.

00:38:22.560 --> 00:38:23.770
There's one on the peninsula.

00:38:23.770 --> 00:38:24.550
I helped train.

00:38:24.550 --> 00:38:26.710
There's one in
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:28.080
that I helped work with.

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:30.840
There's one in
Northwest Connecticut.

00:38:30.840 --> 00:38:32.675
And there's a great
one in Toronto

00:38:32.675 --> 00:38:34.300
that I didn't have
anything to do with.

00:38:34.300 --> 00:38:38.830
But food waste is
becoming a huge topic.

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:44.440
And I even saw it on the
side of a moving van.

00:38:44.440 --> 00:38:47.170
I can't remember the name
of the moving company,

00:38:47.170 --> 00:38:53.920
but it had a big sign on it
saying moveforhunger.org.

00:38:53.920 --> 00:38:56.980
And it appears that
the moving company

00:38:56.980 --> 00:39:00.160
that's getting
all your furniture

00:39:00.160 --> 00:39:02.620
and taking it
somewhere will also

00:39:02.620 --> 00:39:06.130
take all your food from your
cupboards and donate it.

00:39:06.130 --> 00:39:09.040
So food waste is becoming
a really good topic.

00:39:09.040 --> 00:39:13.030
And it's great that everybody
is becoming involved in it.

00:39:16.800 --> 00:39:17.820
Any other questions?

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.280
So the other thing that
I am going to finish with

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:31.500
is, I know that most of you are
trained professionals in food.

00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:36.730
And I want to tell
you a story about--

00:39:36.730 --> 00:39:42.540
so we had a truck donated
to us 20 years ago from UPS,

00:39:42.540 --> 00:39:45.270
and it was a refrigerated truck.

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:49.980
And so I went to a party
at the middle of the night,

00:39:49.980 --> 00:39:52.830
put all the donated food in it.

00:39:55.920 --> 00:39:59.700
We used a parking space
at Royal Hawaiian Seafood

00:39:59.700 --> 00:40:00.930
and plugged it in.

00:40:00.930 --> 00:40:02.110
I plugged in.

00:40:02.110 --> 00:40:04.680
But the next day I went
back to get the truck

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:07.500
to deliver the food
to the shelters

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:14.680
and it was clear that the
refrigeration didn't work.

00:40:14.680 --> 00:40:21.450
And so I had big bags of carrots
and celery, bread, and bags

00:40:21.450 --> 00:40:23.970
of cooked chicken.

00:40:23.970 --> 00:40:29.220
And so what I did was I drove
the truck to 5th and Bryant,

00:40:29.220 --> 00:40:31.380
to the shelter at
5th and Bryant,

00:40:31.380 --> 00:40:37.110
and taking the bags
of bread inside,

00:40:37.110 --> 00:40:38.790
taking the carrots inside.

00:40:38.790 --> 00:40:42.360
And I tried to put the
chicken into the dumpster.

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:45.600
And the homeless guys that were
waiting to get in the shelter

00:40:45.600 --> 00:40:47.460
started climbing
in the dumpster.

00:40:47.460 --> 00:40:49.670
And I'm like, oh, no,
no, you can't eat that.

00:40:49.670 --> 00:40:51.450
It'll make you sick.

00:40:51.450 --> 00:40:54.480
And they go, "Lady,
we're hungry."

00:40:54.480 --> 00:40:59.940
You know, there's no
need to fear liability.

00:40:59.940 --> 00:41:02.520
And I don't care what the
health department says

00:41:02.520 --> 00:41:06.090
in San Francisco or
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania

00:41:06.090 --> 00:41:07.710
or Truckee, California.

00:41:11.250 --> 00:41:13.050
If you let the
health department--

00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:15.780
I mean of course you have
to obey their rules when

00:41:15.780 --> 00:41:17.540
you're in the food business.

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:21.090
But they will try
and tell you, oh, it

00:41:21.090 --> 00:41:23.880
has to be chilled at this
temperature and raised to the--

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:25.960
and take the
fucking temperature.

00:41:25.960 --> 00:41:30.097
No, it's food and
they're hungry people.

00:41:30.097 --> 00:41:32.430
They're not going to follow
you out the door to find out

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:35.520
where the salad is going.

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:38.825
I'm an old hippie from the '60s.

00:41:46.540 --> 00:41:49.650
We can't be run by
rules and regulations

00:41:49.650 --> 00:41:51.160
when there are hungry people.

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:54.210
And we have to, as
civilized human beings,

00:41:54.210 --> 00:41:57.120
we have to take care of
our fellow human beings.

00:41:57.120 --> 00:41:59.850
As far as I know,
we're the only animal

00:41:59.850 --> 00:42:04.050
in the world that heats food
and makes it taste good.

00:42:07.410 --> 00:42:13.170
We aren't like deer or raccoons
going around the Presidio

00:42:13.170 --> 00:42:14.140
picking up food.

00:42:17.460 --> 00:42:20.400
And we have to take care
of our fellow human beings.

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:24.450
And with one out of
every four people

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:26.640
going to bed hungry
in San Francisco,

00:42:26.640 --> 00:42:30.650
we need to do everything
we can to help them.

00:42:30.650 --> 00:42:31.820
Thank you.

00:42:31.820 --> 00:42:35.770
[APPLAUSE]

